WebHooks:
A webhook is a notification from GitHub (or GitLab/Bitbucket) to Jenkins
Instead of Jenkins polling: Git pushes event → Jenkins immediately starts build 

Flow :

Developer pushes code
GitHub triggers webhook
Jenkins receives request
Pipeline starts automatically

Step-by-Step Git Webhook Setup
Step 1: Install Required Plugin in Jenkins
Go to: Manage Jenkins → Manage Plugins 
Install: Git plugin & GitHub Integration plugin 

Step 2: Configure Jenkins Job
For Pipeline Job:
Go to your job → Configure
✔ Enable: Build Triggers → GitHub hook trigger for GITScm polling

Step 3: Get Jenkins Webhook URL
http://<jenkins-ip>:8080/github-webhook/    # must end with github-webhook

Step 4: Add Webhook in GitHub
Go to your repo: Settings → Webhooks → Add webhook

Step 5: Configure Webhook:
Fill:

| Field        | Value                                      |
| ------------ | ------------------------------------------ |
| Payload URL  | `http://<jenkins-ip>:8080/github-webhook/` |
| Content type | `application/json`                         |
| Events       | Just the push event                        |

Step 6: Save
✔ Webhook created

Step 7: Test It
Make a commit:
git add .
git commit -m "test webhook"
git push
